  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Acute aortic dissection is a life-threatening condition characterized by separation of the layers of the aortic wall by blood, with creation of a false lumen. The classic presentation is the acute onset of severe, 'tearing' chest pain that often radiates to the back or abdomen. On physical examination, a discrepancy in blood pressure between the two arms (>20 mmHg) suggests aortic branch vessel involvement. A diastolic murmur of aortic regurgitation may be present. Chest CT with contrast is the most commonly used imaging modality. Stanford type A dissections involve the ascending aorta and require emergency surgery; type B dissections are limited to the descending aorta and are often managed medically. The initial medical management focuses on pain control and reduction of systolic blood pressure (goal 100-120 mmHg) and cardiac contractility (dp/dt). Intravenous beta-blockers (e.g., esmolol or labetalol) are first-line agents to reduce heart rate (target <60 bpm) and blood pressure.",
