  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a condition that develops when the reflux of stomach contents causes troublesome symptoms and/or complications. The two most common symptoms of GERD are heartburn and regurgitation. Heartburn is characterized by a retrosternal burning sensation that typically occurs after meals and worsens when lying down. Regurgitation is defined as the perception of flow of refluxed gastric content into the mouth or hypopharynx. Other common symptoms include dysphagia, chest pain, and extraesophageal manifestations such as chronic cough, hoarseness, and globus sensation. The diagnosis of GERD is typically based on a combination of symptom presentation, response to acid suppression, and objective testing with either upper endoscopy or ambulatory reflux monitoring.",
