  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Pleurisy or pleuritis refers to inflammation of the pleura, typically causing sharp, localized chest pain that worsens with inspiration and coughing. The pain may be referred to the shoulder or abdomen. A pleural friction rub, a creaking or grating sound synchronous with respiration, may be heard on auscultation. Causes of pleurisy include viral infections (particularly influenza, coxsackievirus, and SARS-CoV-2), bacterial pneumonia, pulmonary embolism with infarction, autoimmune disorders (like lupus or rheumatoid arthritis), and drug reactions. Viral pleurisy often follows upper respiratory tract infections and is typically self-limited. Imaging findings may include pleural thickening, small pleural effusions, and subtle parenchymal opacities adjacent to the affected pleura. Treatment is directed at the underlying cause, with NSAIDs often providing symptomatic relief.",
