  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Massive pulmonary embolism is defined as pulmonary embolism with hemodynamic instability (systolic blood pressure <90 mmHg or a drop of ≥40 mmHg for >15 minutes). It is a life-threatening condition with a mortality rate of >50% if untreated. Systemic thrombolytic therapy is indicated for massive pulmonary embolism with hemodynamic compromise in the absence of contraindications. Thrombolytic agents, such as tissue plasminogen activator (t-PA), accelerate the lysis of pulmonary emboli and lead to more rapid improvement in pulmonary obstruction, pulmonary artery pressure, and right ventricular function compared to anticoagulation alone. Contraindications to thrombolytic therapy include active internal bleeding, recent cerebrovascular accident, recent surgery or trauma, and known bleeding diathesis. If thrombolysis is contraindicated or has failed, catheter-based interventions or surgical embolectomy may be considered.",
